description.narrative:
FN:s befolkningsfond (UNFPA) i Sydsudan har ansökt om ett icke-öronmärkt stöd från Sida på 120 miljoner SEK för att implementera sitt landprogram för Sydsudan under åren 2019-2021.
UNFPA:s landprogram för Sydsudan fokuserar på fyra mål.
1. Sexuell och reproduktiv hälsa och rättigheter:
Aktiviteter för att säkerställa att konfliktdrabbade befolkningsgrupper, särskilt kvinnor och ungdomar, får ökad tillgång till information och service inom t.ex. mödrahälsa, familjeplanering, könsbaserat våld och hiv-prevention.
Aktiviteter för att säkerställa att nationella system, särskilt för mödrahälsa och familjeplanering, stärks för tillhandahållandet av integrerad information om sexuell reproduktiv hälsa och rättigheter (SRHR) samt tillgång till relaterade service samt för ansvarsutkrävning avseende SRHR.
2. Unga människor:
Aktiviteter för att säkerställa att unga människor kan bättre fatta välgrundade beslut avseende deras SRHR och delta i planering, genomförande och utvärdering av fredsbyggande, utvecklings- och humanitära policyer och program.
3. Jämställdhet och kvinnors egenmakt:
Aktiviteter för att säkerställa ökad multisektoriell kapacitet för att förhindra och bemöta könsrelaterat våld och skadliga normer, inklusive barnäktenskap.
4. Befolkningsdynamik:
Insatser för att förbättra nationella system för generering och spridning av befolkningsdata och demografisk information. Detta ska även tillämpas i humanitära förhållanden.
Den totala budgeten för UNFPA:s landprogram uppgår till 55 miljoner USD varav 36 miljoner USD i nuläget har säkrats (inkluderar Sidas tänkta bidrag på motsvarande 13,5 miljoner USD). UNFPA bidrar själv med 7,8 miljoner USD, Norge med 4,5 miljoner USD och Kanada med 10 miljoner USD. UNFPA har som målsättning att mobilisera resterande 19 miljoner USD (gapet mellan budget och hittills säkrad finansiering).
UNFPA:s landprogram kommer till stor del att genomföras av ett flertal implementeringspartners (cirka 15 stycken). UNFPA kommer därför att vidareförmedla ungefär 60 procent av Sidas bidrag till implementeringspartners.
Omkring 80 procent av den totala budgeten är avsedd för genomförandet av insatser som är fokuserade på SRHR (det första målet).
I genomförandet kommer UNFPA även att samarbeta med övriga FN-systemet i Sydsudan, speciellt med UN Women, och andra givare inom ramen för givarfonden, Health Pooled Fund. Detta är betydelsefullt, speciellt eftersom Sida i nuläget arbetar med beredningar avseende eventuellt stöd till både UN Women och Health Pooled Fund i Sydsudan.

The UN Population Fund (UNFPA) in South Sudan has submitted a funding application to Sida regarding unearmarked support amounting to a total of 120 million SEK in order to implement its country program for South Sudan.
The UNFPA South Sudan country program focuses on four goals.
1. Sexual and reproductive health and rights:
Activities to ensure that crisis affected populations, particularly women and adolescent girls, have increased access to information and services regarding e.g., maternal health, family planning, gender-based violence and HIV prevention.
Activities to ensure that national systems, especially for maternal health and family planning, are strengthened for the provision of integrated information on sexual reproductive health rights (SRHR) and access to services and as well as for accountability on SRHR.
2. Young people:
Activities to ensure that young people are better able to make informed decisions on regarding their SRHR, and to participate in the planning, implementation and evaluation of peace-building, development and humanitarian policies and programs.
3. Gender equality and women’s empowerment:
Activities to ensure increased multi-sectoral capacity to prevent and respond to gender-based violence and harmful norms, including child marriage.
4. Population dynamics:
Activities to ensure improved national systems for generation and dissemination of population data and demographic information, including in humanitarian settings.
The total budget for the UNFPA South Sudan country program amounts to USD 55 million, out of which USD 36 million have currently been secured (includes the expected Sida contribution of the equivalence of USD 13.5 million). UNFPA will out of its own resources contribute USD 7.8 million; Norway with USD 4.5 million; and, Canada with USD 10 million. The ambition of UNFPA is to mobilize the remaining USD 19 million (i.e., the gap between the budget and thus far secured funds).
The UNFPA South Sudan country program will largely be implemented by several implementing partners (approximately 15). UNFPA will therefore forward about 60 percent of the Sida contribution to implementing partners.
Approximately 80 percent of the total budget is dedicated to the implementation of activities that are focused on SRHR (the first goal).
During the course of implementation, UNFPA will also collaborate with the rest of the UN-system in South Sudan, especially with UN Women, and other donors within the context of the donor fund, Health Pooled Fund. This is important, especially since Sida is currently assessing potential support to both UN Women and the Health Pooled Fund in South Sudan.

The UNFPA country program for South Sudan focuses on four outcome areas with five articulated objectives as presented below. Sida considers that the outcomes and objectives are clear and in line with the mandate and comparative advantages of UNFPA as the lead within the UN system concerning the outcomes and objectives. Sida also concludes that the outcomes and objectives are highly relevant for the South Sudan context and in support of the relevant Sida strategies i.e., clearly contributing towards their attainment. 1: Sexual and reproductive health and rights -Crisis affected populations, particularly women and adolescent girls, have increased access to information and services for maternal health, family planning, gender-based violence (GBV) and HIV prevention in emergency and fragile contexts. -National systems, especially for maternal health and family planning, are strengthened for the provision of integrated sexual reproductive health information and services and for accountability on sexual reproductive health and rights (SRHR). 2: Adolescents and youth -Adolescents and youth are better able to make informed decisions on their SRHR, and to participate in planning, implementation and evaluation of peace-building, development and humanitarian policies and programs. 3: Gender equality and womens empowerment -Increased multi-sectoral capacity to prevent and respond to GBV and harmful practices, including child marriage. 4: Population dynamics -Improved national systems for generation and dissemination of population data and demographic intelligence, including in humanitarian settings.

tag.narrative: 3.1 - By 2030, reduce the global maternal mortality ratio to less than 70 per 100,000 live births.
3.1 - Till 2030 minska mödradödligheten i världen till mindre än 70 dödsfall per 100 000 förlossningar med levande barn.

3.2 - By 2030, end preventable deaths of newborns and children under 5 years of age, with all countries aiming to reduce neonatal mortality to at least as low as 12 per 1,000 live births and under-5 mortality to at least as low as 25 per 1,000 live births.

3.2 - Senast 2030 säkerställa att inga spädbarn eller barn under fem år dör av orsaker som hade kunnat förebyggas. Alla länder bör sträva efter att minska den neonatala dödligheten till högst tolv dödsfall per 1 000 levande födda och dödligheten bland barn under fem år till högst 25 dödsfall per 1 000 levande födda.

3.7 - By 2030, ensure universal access to sexual and reproductive health-care services, including for family planning, information and education, and the integration of reproductive health into national strategies and programmes.

3.7 - Senast 2030 säkerställa att alla har tillgång till sexuell och reproduktiv hälsovård, inklusive familjeplanering, information och utbildning, och att reproduktiv hälsa integreras i nationella strategier och program.

description.narrative: The year 2020 was the second year of the UNFPA South Sudan 3rd Country Programme (2019-2021). The programme focuses on the following 5 results areas -Increased access to information and services for maternal health, family planning, gender-based violence and HIV prevention for crisis affected populations, particularly women and adolescent girls -Strengthened national systems for the provision of integrated sexual and reproductive health information and services and accountability for sexual reproductive health and rights -Improved participation of adolescents and youth in planning, implementation and evaluation of peace building, development and humanitarian policies and programmes -Increased multi-sectoral capacity to prevent and respond to gender-based violence and harmful practices, including child marriage. -Improved national systems for generation and dissemination of population data and demographic intelligence. At the end of first quarter (March 2020),South Sudan was faced with the global COVID19 pandemic that that resulted in lock down and related restrictions that paralyzed implementation during quarter two (April to June 2020). During the 3rd quarter, implementation of the programme activities rebounded as UNFPA and partners put in place coping mechanisms. Reprogramming was done; the partners and UNFPA included COVID19 prevention measures in the work plans. Implementation of the mainstream work plan activities was done as an integral part of implementation of COVID19 prevention activities mainly Risk Communication and Engagement as well as infection Prevention and Control. The focus was to ensure continuity of implementation of the work plan particularly provision of SRH/GBV services and information amid the COVID19 restrictions and lock down. However, a number of activities were affected by COVID19 and the achievement of related targets remained behind schedule particularly in relation to fistula treatment, activities that involved working with schools and training institutions that were closed from March to October and engagement with key government staff to push forward key policy and legislative frameworks. Below is a small selection of results achieved from 2020: Focus area: Adolescent and Youth Friendly SRH Services (YFS centres: Juba TH, Kapoeta, Torit, Maridi, Yambio, Aweil and Mingkaman by AMREF, IHO, ADRA, IRC and IMA) Indicator 1) Number of adolescents and youth were provided with integrated SRH/HIV/GBV services 2020 Target Achieved 1) 300 000 198 200 (65%) Comment:Limited Adolescent SRH outreaches due to COVID19 affected reaching the out of school youth 2) Number of young people reached with information on SRH 2020 Target Achieved 500 000 505 618 (101%) Comment: Number of adolescents and youth in secondary schools and universities provided with SRH/HIV and Comprehensive Sexuality Education (CSE) information 2020 Target Achieved 40 000 28 178 (70%) Comment: Closure of education institutions due to COVID19 affected CSE activities.
